Isi tarah continue...

Answer:
[3,3,5,5,6,7]

❓ WHY DEQUE
- Front se maximum instantly milta hai.
- Back se useless smaller elements remove kar sakte hain.
- Deque decreasing order maintain karta hai.

Example:

[5,3,2]

Agar 6 aaya:

5,3,2 sab future me kabhi max nahi ban sakte.

Direct remove karke:

[6]

⏱️ COMPLEXITY
Time  : O(N)

Reason:
- Har element maximum ek baar insert hota hai.
- Har element maximum ek baar remove hota hai.

Space : O(K)

🎯 INTERVIEW POINT
- Deque always decreasing order me maintain hota hai.
- Front = current window maximum.
- Smaller elements back se remove karna sabse important observation hai.
- Ye code values store kar raha hai, indices nahi.
- Outgoing element remove tabhi hoga jab wo deque ke front par ho.
- Sliding Window Maximum ka standard pattern:
  "Monotonic Decreasing Deque".

#Code:

import java.util.*;

public class Solution
{
    public static List<Integer> maxSlidingWindow(int[] nums, int k)
    {
        //You can code here
        ArrayDeque<Integer> dq = new ArrayDeque<>();
        List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();

        int i = 0;
        while(i < k){
          while(!dq.isEmpty() && dq.getLast() < nums[i]){
            dq.pollLast();
          }
          dq.offerLast(nums[i]);
          i++;
        }
        int n = nums.length;
        for(; i<n; i++){
          ans.add(dq.peekFirst());
          if(dq.peekFirst() == nums[i-k]){
            dq.pollFirst();
          }
          while(!dq.isEmpty() && dq.getLast() < nums[i]){
            dq.pollLast();
          }
          dq.offerLast(nums[i]);
        }
        ans.add(dq.peekFirst());

        return ans;
      
    }
}
